# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: helicopter
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:helicopter/1977-israeli-ch-53-crash] On 10 May 1977, an Israeli Air Force **Sikorsky CH-53 *Yas'ur* helicopter crashed** during an exercise in the Jordan Valley, killing all 54 on board (including the 10-member flight crew).
[src:helicopter/1977-israeli-ch-53-crash] The disaster became known as *Ason HaNun-Daled*, or "Disaster of the 54".
[src:helicopter/1977-israeli-ch-53-crash] It remains the worst single-aircraft accident in the West Bank.
[src:helicopter/1977-israeli-ch-53-crash] The crash site was in the Jordan Valley, near the Israeli settlement of Na'aran, north of Jericho in a wadi.
[src:helicopter/1977-israeli-ch-53-crash] The cause was determined to be flying at too low an altitude during the dark, which caused the helicopter to strike a hill, crash and explode (CFIT, Controlled flight into terrain).
[src:helicopter/1986-british-international-helicopters-chinook-crash] On 6 November 1986, a Boeing-Vertol Model 234LR Chinook helicopter returning workers from the Brent oilfield crashed on approach to land at Sumburgh Airport in the Shetland Islands.
[src:helicopter/1986-british-international-helicopters-chinook-crash] At 2.5 mi (4.0 km) from the runway the helicopter had a catastrophic forward transmission failure which caused the tandem rotor blades to collide.
[src:helicopter/1986-british-international-helicopters-chinook-crash] The helicopter crashed into the sea and sank.
[src:helicopter/1986-british-international-helicopters-chinook-crash] Forty-three passengers and two crew members were killed in the crash; one passenger and one crew member survived with injuries.
[src:helicopter/1986-british-international-helicopters-chinook-crash] The flight crew of the Chinook consisted of Captain Pushp Vaid (45), a former Indian Air Force pilot who joined British International Helicopters in 1975 and started to fly the Chinook in 1982.
[src:helicopter/1986-british-international-helicopters-chinook-crash] His co-pilot was First Officer Neville Nixon (43), who left Bristow Helicopters in order to help his wife run a chemist's shop and returned to flying after helping his wife, albeit now working in British International Helicopters.
[src:helicopter/1986-british-international-helicopters-chinook-crash] Captain Vaid survived while First Officer Nixon did not.
[src:helicopter/1986-british-international-helicopters-chinook-crash] The helicopter was normally based at Aberdeen Airport but had been based at Sumburgh Airport since 3 November 1986 to operate a shuttle service from the Brent oilfield in the East Shetland Basin.
[src:helicopter/1986-british-international-helicopters-chinook-crash] On 6 November the first flight was delayed due to an oil leak from an engine gearbox that was soon rectified and the aircraft left Sumburgh at 08:58 with 40 passengers for the Brent Field.
[src:helicopter/1986-british-international-helicopters-chinook-crash] The aircraft visited three platforms with exchanges of freight and passengers then departed Brent Platform *C* at 10:22 with 44 passengers on board for return to Sumburgh Airport.
[src:helicopter/1986-british-international-helicopters-chinook-crash] It transited at a height of 2,500 feet (800 m), and as it approached Sumburgh it was cleared to descend to 1,000 feet (300 m).
[src:helicopter/1986-british-international-helicopters-chinook-crash] Reporting 4.5 miles (7.2 km) from the airfield, the controller cleared it to land on helicopter runway 24.
[src:helicopter/1986-british-international-helicopters-chinook-crash] The voice recorder indicated that the crew noticed an increased noise level in the flightdeck followed by a bang.
[src:helicopter/1986-british-international-helicopters-chinook-crash] Despite applying full cyclic pitch control, the aircraft did not respond and fell towards the sea from a height of 150 feet (50 m).
[src:helicopter/1986-british-international-helicopters-chinook-crash] The helicopter was largely broken up by the clashing rotor blades in mid air, hit the sea and quickly sank.
[src:helicopter/1986-british-international-helicopters-chinook-crash] A Coastguard search and rescue Sikorsky S-61 helicopter which had just departed Sumburgh Airport on training flight reported liferafts in the sea.
[src:helicopter/1986-british-international-helicopters-chinook-crash] It then observed a survivor clinging to a substantial piece of wreckage.
[src:helicopter/1986-british-international-helicopters-chinook-crash] While they winched the man on board another survivor was noted among the floating bodies.
[src:helicopter/1986-british-international-helicopters-chinook-crash] With no signs of other survivors the Coastguard helicopter flew the survivors to Lerwick for transfer to hospital.
[src:helicopter/1986-british-international-helicopters-chinook-crash] An air and sea search failed to find any more survivors but all the floating bodies were recovered and brought to the airport.
[src:helicopter/1986-british-international-helicopters-chinook-crash] One of the flight crew and the flight attendant were among the dead.
[src:helicopter/1986-british-international-helicopters-chinook-crash] A diving support vessel, the MSV *Deepwater 1* (now named *Rockwater 1*), started a search for the sunken wreckage at 09:00 the following morning.
[src:helicopter/1986-british-international-helicopters-chinook-crash] Sea conditions were rough with strong tidal currents and a water depth around 90 metres but the wreckage was located.
[src:helicopter/1986-british-international-helicopters-chinook-crash] The monohulled *Deepwater 1* struggled to maintain position in the building sea and current conditions.
[src:helicopter/1986-british-international-helicopters-chinook-crash] Shell Expro's Multi Services Vessel, the MSV *Stadive*, arrived and assumed the role of primary recovery vessel and, being a semi-submersible, was able to quickly recover the major components of interest.
[src:helicopter/1986-british-international-helicopters-chinook-crash] The *Stadive* remained on site and recovered much of the remainder of the fuselage and the bodies of the victims.
[src:helicopter/1986-british-international-helicopters-chinook-crash] In all, 44 of the 45 victims' bodies were recovered.
[src:helicopter/1986-british-international-helicopters-chinook-crash] The accident was caused by the failure of a modified bevel ring gear in the forward transmission which allowed the twin rotors to collide when synchronisation was lost.
[src:helicopter/1986-british-international-helicopters-chinook-crash] The AAIB stated that the underlying causes were the inadequacy of a previously accepted test programme and the failure of a stringent inspection programme.
[src:helicopter/1986-british-international-helicopters-chinook-crash] The oil industry decided that the Chinook was too big for the offshore support task and the remaining Chinooks were withdrawn and sold.
[src:helicopter/1986-british-international-helicopters-chinook-crash] All surviving aircraft now operate with Columbia Helicopters in heavy lift, non-passenger capabilities.
[src:helicopter/1992-azerbaijani-mil-mi-8-shootdown] On January 28, 1992, Azerbaijani transport helicopter Mil Mi-8 was shot down by a heat-seeking missile near the town of Shusha.
[src:helicopter/1992-azerbaijani-mil-mi-8-shootdown] Federal Aviation Administration on aviation security called it the "most significant incident" involving civil aviation in Central Eurasia.
[src:helicopter/1992-azerbaijani-mil-mi-8-shootdown] Serious air warfare during the Nagorno-Karabakh War broke out in January 1992.
[src:helicopter/1992-azerbaijani-mil-mi-8-shootdown] Azeri aircraft became easy targets for Armenian armed forces.
[src:helicopter/1992-azerbaijani-mil-mi-8-shootdown] On January 9, the Armenians first claimed to have shot down an Azeri helicopter.
[src:helicopter/1992-azerbaijani-mil-mi-8-shootdown] More claims followed on January 24, 28 and 31 – all of them over Nagorno-Karabakh, the last being a Mi-8 downed from MANPADs over the village of Huha.
[src:helicopter/1992-azerbaijani-mil-mi-8-shootdown] On January 31, the Azeris claimed the downings of two Mi-8s that supported the first Armenian offensive.
[src:helicopter/1992-azerbaijani-mil-mi-8-shootdown] The Mi-8 helicopter transported 44 persons aboard (41 passengers, all civilians, and 3 crew) when it departed the town of Aghdam for Shusha, which was blockaded by Armenians.
[src:helicopter/1992-azerbaijani-mil-mi-8-shootdown] The craft was downed en route by a surface-to-air missile.
[src:helicopter/1992-azerbaijani-mil-mi-8-shootdown] According to Azeri journalist Kerim Kerimli, who assisted in collecting bodies at the site and confirmed the number of fatalities, the missile was launched from Xankəndi.
[src:helicopter/1992-azerbaijani-mil-mi-8-shootdown] Armenian officials stated that the helicopter was carrying weapons and ammunition to Azeris attacking Armenian villages.
[src:helicopter/1997-israeli-helicopter-disaster] The **1997 Israeli helicopter disaster** (Hebrew: אסון המסוקים, romanized: *Ason HaMasokim*, lit.
[src:helicopter/1997-israeli-helicopter-disaster] ''Disaster of the Helicopters'') occurred on February 4, 1997, when two Israeli Air Force transport helicopters ferrying Israeli soldiers into Israel's security zone in southern Lebanon collided in mid-air, killing all 73 Israeli military personnel on board.
[src:helicopter/1997-israeli-helicopter-disaster] The crash brought about widespread national mourning and is considered a leading factor in Israel's decision to withdraw from southern Lebanon in 2000.
[src:helicopter/1997-israeli-helicopter-disaster] Following the 1982 Lebanon War, Israel had withdrawn to a "security zone" in southern Lebanon, where it faced an insurgency by Hezbollah and other Lebanese groups.
[src:helicopter/1997-israeli-helicopter-disaster] Israel had originally moved troops by ground, but this policy was changed as the threat of roadside bombs increased.
[src:helicopter/1997-israeli-helicopter-disaster] As a result, Israel increasingly began ferrying soldiers by air into southern Lebanon.
[src:helicopter/1997-israeli-helicopter-disaster] Two Sikorsky S-65C-3 Yas'ur 2000 helicopters, *357* and *903*, were assigned on a mission to fly Israeli soldiers and munitions into southern Lebanon, originally scheduled for February 3, but postponed a day due to bad weather conditions.
[src:helicopter/1997-israeli-helicopter-disaster] On February 4, the weather conditions were still poor for flying due to fog.
[src:helicopter/1997-israeli-helicopter-disaster] In the afternoon visibility improved, and the mission was allowed to go forward.
[src:helicopter/1997-israeli-helicopter-disaster] The two helicopters took off from Tel Nof Airbase and flew to Rosh Pina Airport, from where they collected the troops.
[src:helicopter/1997-israeli-helicopter-disaster] One helicopter, numbered *903*, was designated to fly to the "Pumpkin" Outpost, east of Nabatiyeh, and had four crew and 32 passengers on board.
[src:helicopter/1997-israeli-helicopter-disaster] The second helicopter, *357*, was to fly to an Israeli position at Beaufort Castle, and had four crew and 33 passengers on board.
[src:helicopter/1997-israeli-helicopter-disaster] At 6:48 PM, after final approval was given and the soldiers had been briefed, both helicopters were cleared to take off.
[src:helicopter/1997-israeli-helicopter-disaster] A minute after takeoff, the captain of the helicopter *903* requested permission from air traffic control to cross the border into Lebanon.
[src:helicopter/1997-israeli-helicopter-disaster] Permission was delayed, and the helicopters ended up hovering until 6:56 PM, when a controller confirmed that they had permission to cross.
[src:helicopter/1997-israeli-helicopter-disaster] Three minutes later, the helicopters disappeared from radar.
[src:helicopter/1997-israeli-helicopter-disaster] The two helicopters collided over moshav She'ar Yashuv in northern Israel.
[src:helicopter/1997-israeli-helicopter-disaster] An Israeli investigation concluded that the rotor of helicopter *357* struck the tail of helicopter *903*.
[src:helicopter/1997-israeli-helicopter-disaster] Helicopter *357* immediately crashed, while the crew of helicopter *903* attempted to take control of it, but failed, and it crashed as well.
[src:helicopter/1997-israeli-helicopter-disaster] According to one witness who observed the event from the ground, "Two helicopters passed over my house without their lights on.
[src:helicopter/1997-israeli-helicopter-disaster] One fell straight away and the other wavered for half a kilometre... then it also exploded." One of the helicopters crashed in a fireball directly onto She'ar Yashuv, setting an empty bungalow on fire, while the other crashed into the cemetery of kibbutz Dafna a few hundred metres away.
[src:helicopter/1997-israeli-helicopter-disaster] Fires, fueled by jet fuel from the helicopters, broke out on the ground, and munitions that had been stored aboard the helicopters cooked off and set off a series of explosions.
[src:helicopter/1997-israeli-helicopter-disaster] Some witnesses claimed they could hear faint cries coming from the wreckage, but they could not get close to them because of the explosions, and that the cries ceased after the explosions.
[src:helicopter/1997-israeli-helicopter-disaster] One witness claimed to have seen a soldier thrown from a helicopter who initially still had a pulse, but died soon after.
[src:helicopter/1997-israeli-helicopter-disaster] All 73 soldiers on the helicopters were killed.
[src:helicopter/1997-israeli-helicopter-disaster] Following the crash, soldiers, firefighters, and rescue crews raced to the scene.
[src:helicopter/1997-israeli-helicopter-disaster] Magen David Adom rushed twenty ambulances and two mobile intensive care units to the scene.
[src:helicopter/1997-israeli-helicopter-disaster] However, it soon became clear there were no survivors.
[src:helicopter/1997-israeli-helicopter-disaster] Fearing that additional ammunition could explode, the IDF cordoned off all communities in the area, declaring them closed military zones, shut down all local roads, and sent in bomb squads to clear the area of explosives.
[src:helicopter/1997-israeli-helicopter-disaster] This created massive traffic jams and temporarily prevented hundreds of people from reaching their homes.
[src:helicopter/1997-israeli-helicopter-disaster] Rescue crews recovered bodies and pieces of equipment from the scene, and some of the dead were found still strapped into their seats.
[src:helicopter/1997-israeli-helicopter-disaster] The bodies were taken to a makeshift morgue set up on a nearby military base for identification.
[src:helicopter/1997-israeli-helicopter-disaster] The IDF censored news of the crash for more than two hours to enable the families of the victims to be informed, but swift identification proved impossible.
[src:helicopter/1997-israeli-helicopter-disaster] All of the bodies had been recovered by the morning of February 5.
[src:helicopter/1997-israeli-helicopter-disaster] The crash was the deadliest air disaster in Israeli history.
[src:helicopter/1997-israeli-helicopter-disaster] A wave of national mourning swept Israel.
[src:helicopter/1997-israeli-helicopter-disaster] February 6 was declared an official day of mourning.
[src:helicopter/1997-israeli-helicopter-disaster] Flags were flown at half-mast, restaurants and cinemas closed, the Knesset observed a minute of silence, and the names of the dead were read out at the beginning of every news bulletin on television and radio.
[src:helicopter/1997-israeli-helicopter-disaster] Thousands of Israelis went to pray at the Western Wall and assemblies were held at schools nationwide.
[src:helicopter/1997-israeli-helicopter-disaster] The funerals began taking place on February 5.
[src:helicopter/1997-israeli-helicopter-disaster] Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu and President Ezer Weizman attended funerals and visited the grieving families.
[src:helicopter/1997-israeli-helicopter-disaster] Israeli Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai appointed a commission of inquiry headed by David Ivry to investigate the cause of the collision.
[src:helicopter/1997-israeli-helicopter-disaster] It recommended that the Israeli Air Force install black boxes in its helicopters.
[src:helicopter/1997-israeli-helicopter-disaster] The disaster sparked renewed debate about Israel's occupation of southern Lebanon.
[src:helicopter/1997-israeli-helicopter-disaster] Later that year, the Four Mothers, an anti-war protest movement dedicated to pressing for an Israeli withdrawal from southern Lebanon, was founded.
[src:helicopter/1997-israeli-helicopter-disaster] This event is seen as a catalyst for Israel's withdrawal from the security zone in Lebanon in 2000.
[src:helicopter/1997-israeli-helicopter-disaster] A memorial to the 73 dead IDF soldiers was created near the crash site of one helicopter next to the cemetery of kibbutz Dafna.
[src:helicopter/1997-israeli-helicopter-disaster] The memorial consists of a number of elements, the most visible being 73 stones erected around a round pool to which water is directed through a channel.
[src:helicopter/1997-israeli-helicopter-disaster] The 73 names are written on black blocks placed under the water of the pool.
[src:helicopter/1997-israeli-helicopter-disaster] A Bible verse from Job 41:17 is inscribed.
[src:helicopter/1997-israeli-helicopter-disaster] The monument was designed by architect Shlomit Shlomo, landscape architects Haim Cohen and Gilad Sharon, sculptor Rami Feldstein; sculptor Dani Karavan acted as an adviser for the project.
[src:helicopter/1997-israeli-helicopter-disaster] In moshav She'ar Yashuv, where the second helicopter crashed, another monument was erected.
[src:helicopter/1997-israeli-helicopter-disaster] On the southeast edge of the moshav, the "Forest of the Fallen" was planted to memorize the dead.
[src:helicopter/1997-israeli-helicopter-disaster] The forest has 73 trees, one for each victim of the crash.
[src:helicopter/1997-israeli-helicopter-disaster] There are numerous other memorial monuments throughout Israel commemorating the disaster.
[src:helicopter/1997-israeli-helicopter-disaster] In addition, there exist memorials for individual soldiers in the places where they lived.
[src:helicopter/1997-israeli-helicopter-disaster] On February 15, 2017, a memorial service was held in Kibbutz Dafna to mark the 20th anniversary of the disaster.
[src:helicopter/1997-israeli-helicopter-disaster] Bereaved families of the victims attended, as well as President Reuven Rivlin, Defense Minister Avigdor Lieberman, and IDF Chief of Staff Gadi Eizenkot.
[src:helicopter/1st-special-operations-wing] The **1st Special Operations Wing** (1 SOW) at Hurlburt Field, Florida is one of three United States Air Force active duty Special Operations wings and falls under the Air Force Special Operations Command (AFSOC).
[src:helicopter/1st-special-operations-wing] The 1st Special Operations Wing is a successor organization of the **16th Pursuit Group**, one of the 15 original combat air groups formed by the Army before World War II.
[src:helicopter/1st-special-operations-wing] The unit's current emblem was approved on 6 June 1963.
[src:helicopter/1st-special-operations-wing] The 16th Pursuit Group's emblem was approved in 1934.
[src:helicopter/1st-special-operations-wing] It has four lightning bolts—representing the four assigned squadrons—depicting destruction from the sky.
[src:helicopter/1st-special-operations-wing] The beginnings of the 1st Special Operations Wing can be traced to the authorization by the Army Air Service of the 16th Pursuit Group on 24 March 1923 as part of the United States Army Panama Department at Albrook Field, Canal Zone.
[src:helicopter/1st-special-operations-wing] The unit, however, was not activated until 1 December 1932.
[src:helicopter/1st-special-operations-wing] The 16th Pursuit Group spent its entire existence in the defense of the Panama Canal.
[src:helicopter/1st-special-operations-wing] The Group was progressively redesignated, in keeping with the changes sweeping through the Army Air Corps, becoming first the 16th Pursuit Group (Interceptor) in 1939 and finally the 16th Fighter Group in 1942.
[src:helicopter/1st-special-operations-wing] It was disbanded in the Canal Zone on 1 November 1943.
[src:helicopter/1st-special-operations-wing] Although subordinate squadrons assigned to the Group changed over the years the Group headquarters remained at Albrook Field throughout its existence.
[src:helicopter/1st-special-operations-wing] In June 1941, relief for the P-36As arrived in the form of 6 Curtiss P-40Bs and 64 P-40Cs, although, though these were split between the 16th and 32nd Pursuit Groups (the 16th got 32 P-40Cs).
[src:helicopter/1st-special-operations-wing] These new aircraft arrived not a moment too soon, because as of April and May 1941 not fewer than 17 of the Groups P-36As were either unserviceable or awaiting deposition due to either a lack of parts or as a result of the hard use they had endured during the intense training program then ongoing.
[src:helicopter/1st-special-operations-wing] One other P-40C did not have a prop, and all elements of the Group were dispersed at Albrook Field.
[src:helicopter/1st-special-operations-wing] Besides these, the Group had 23 P-40Cs, eight P-40Es and 14 of its former P-36As back at Albrook.
[src:helicopter/1st-special-operations-wing] As the squadrons of the group moved through their various deployments from the start of the war on, the group headquarters became less and less important in day-to-day operations and, finally, on 17 January 1943, the Group Headquarters was moved from Albrook to La Joya Auxiliary Airdrome No.
[src:helicopter/1st-special-operations-wing] 2 to attempt to get the men assigned at Group back into the midst of "field" operations that were being endured by the subordinate squadrons.
[src:helicopter/1st-special-operations-wing] In actuality, the Group was disbanded on 31 October 1943, at which time the HHS still had a solitary Curtiss P-36A assigned.
[src:helicopter/1st-special-operations-wing] The Command and Control responsibilities of the surviving former Squadrons of the Group then came under the umbrella of the XXVI Fighter Command.
[src:helicopter/1st-special-operations-wing] P-47 Thunderbolts of the 1st Air Commando Group, 10th Air Force, taking off.
[src:helicopter/1st-special-operations-wing] Republic P-47D-23-RA Thunderbolt, AAF Ser.
[src:helicopter/1st-special-operations-wing] The next unit in the lineage of the 1 SOW is the 1st Air Commando Group, which inherited the history and lineage of the 16th Fighter Group.
[src:helicopter/1st-special-operations-wing] Roosevelt, amidst the Quebec Conference in August 1943, was impressed by Brigadier Orde Wingate's account of what could be accomplished in Burma with proper air support.
[src:helicopter/1st-special-operations-wing] To comply with Roosevelt's proposed air support for British long range penetration operations in Burma, the United States Army Air Forces created the 5318th Air Unit to support the Chindits.
[src:helicopter/1st-special-operations-wing] In March 1944, they were designated the 1st Air Commando Group by USAAF Commander General Hap Arnold.
[src:helicopter/1st-special-operations-wing] Alison and Colonel Philip Cochran as co-commanders of the unit.
[src:helicopter/1st-special-operations-wing] Alison was a veteran flight instructor of P-40 aircraft, and gained renown as a pilot with Major David Lee "Tex" Hill's 75th Fighter Squadron, part of Col Robert Lee Scott, Jr.'s 23d Fighter Group, the USAAF successor of the AVG's famed Flying Tigers in the China-Burma-India Theater.
[src:helicopter/1st-special-operations-wing] General Claire Lee Chennault lobbied to Arnold, who knew Alison from service at Langley Field, suggesting Alison be given the new command.
[src:helicopter/1st-special-operations-wing] Cochran was a decorated P-40 veteran pilot from the North African Campaign noted for his unconventional aerial tactics.
[src:helicopter/1st-special-operations-wing] As a result, the 5318th Provisional Air Unit was formed in India in late 1943.
[src:helicopter/1st-special-operations-wing] As a miscellaneous unit, the group was comprised until September 1944 of operational sections (rather than units): bomber; fighter; light-plane (and helicopter); transport; glider; and light-cargo.
[src:helicopter/1st-special-operations-wing] The 1st Air Commando Group consisted of a squadron of 30 A-model P-51 Mustangs led by Lt.
[src:helicopter/1st-special-operations-wing] "Grant" Mahony, a squadron of 12 B-25H bombers led by Lt.
[src:helicopter/1st-special-operations-wing] Smith, 13 C-47 air transports led by Major William T.
[src:helicopter/1st-special-operations-wing] Cherry, Jr., 225 Waco CG-4A military gliders led by Captain William H.
[src:helicopter/1st-special-operations-wing] Taylor, Jr., and 100 L-1 and L-5 Sentinel liaison aircraft led by Major Andrew Rebori and Lt.
[src:helicopter/1st-special-operations-wing] The group tested the United States' first use of a helicopter in combat, six Sikorsky R-4s led by Lt.
[src:helicopter/1st-special-operations-wing] A tragic accident occurred where 2 CG-4 gliders towed by one of the unit's Skytrains collided killing several American and British Chindits.
[src:helicopter/1st-special-operations-wing] The unit was redesignated the 1st Air Commando Group on 25 March 1944.
[src:helicopter/1st-special-operations-wing] It provided fighter cover, bomb striking power, and air transport services for the Chindits (Wingate's Raiders), fighting behind enemy lines in Burma.
[src:helicopter/1st-special-operations-wing] Operations included airdrop and landing of troops, food, and equipment; evacuation of casualties; and attacks against enemy airfields and lines of communication.
[src:helicopter/1st-special-operations-wing] The 1ACG started receiving better-performing P-51B Mustangs in April 1944.
[src:helicopter/1st-special-operations-wing] They converted from P-51 Mustang to D-Model P-47 Thunderbolt fighters by September 1945.
[src:helicopter/1st-special-operations-wing] The unit eliminated its B-25 Mitchell bomber section in May 1944.
[src:helicopter/1st-special-operations-wing] In September 1944, after the original unit was consolidated with the headquarters component of the new establishment (also called 1st Air Commando Group), the sections were replaced by a troop carrier squadron, two fighter squadrons, and three liaison squadrons.
[src:helicopter/1st-special-operations-wing] The group continued performing supply, evacuation, and liaison services for allied forces in Burma until the end of the war, including the movement of Chinese troops from Burma to China in December 1944.
[src:helicopter/1st-special-operations-wing] It also attacked bridges, railroads, airfields, barges, oil wells, and troop positions in Burma; and escorted bombers to Burmese targets, including Rangoon.
[src:helicopter/1st-special-operations-wing] Switched back to P-51 Mustangs (D-models) in January 1945.
[src:helicopter/1st-special-operations-wing] Left Burma in October and inactivated in New Jersey in November 1945.
[src:helicopter/1st-special-operations-wing] On 15 March 1945, 40 P-51D Mustangs armed with drop tanks attacked Don Muang airfield, which harbored little more than 100 Japanese aircraft.
[src:helicopter/1st-special-operations-wing] At 1:30 pm (1330 military time), the Mustangs strafed every aircraft in sight, and destroyed at least 50% of the aircraft there.
[src:helicopter/1st-special-operations-wing] More Japanese aircraft that managed to takeoff were shot down and destroyed.
[src:helicopter/1st-special-operations-wing] On 9 April 1945, a second attack was launched with 33 Mustangs total.
[src:helicopter/1st-special-operations-wing] Anti-Aircraft fire was heavy, and three Mustangs were shot down.
[src:helicopter/1st-special-operations-wing] They also used helicopters in combat for the first time, executing the first combat medical evacuations.
[src:helicopter/1st-special-operations-wing] They pioneered the use of air-to-ground rockets.
[src:helicopter/1st-special-operations-wing] These firsts and others had a lasting effect on how air operations would directly support ground operations.
[src:helicopter/1st-special-operations-wing] 4400th CCTS North American T-28A-NA Trojan Serial, AF Ser.
[src:helicopter/1st-special-operations-wing] In response to Lemay's directive, on 14 April 1961 Tactical Air Command activated the 4400th Combat Crew Training Squadron (CCTS) at Hurlburt Field, Florida.
[src:helicopter/1st-special-operations-wing] The unit had an authorized strength of 124 officers and 228 enlisted men.
[src:helicopter/1st-special-operations-wing] The 4400th CCTS consisted of World War II aircraft: 16 C-47 transports, eight B-26 bombers, and eight T-28 fighters.
[src:helicopter/1st-special-operations-wing] The declared mission of the unit would be to train indigenous air forces in counterinsurgency and conduct air operations.
[src:helicopter/1st-special-operations-wing] The 4400th CCTS acquired the logistics code name "Jungle Jim", a moniker that rapidly became the nickname of the unit.
[src:helicopter/1st-special-operations-wing] As the military conditions in South Vietnam continued to deteriorate, United States Secretary of Defense Robert S.
[src:helicopter/1st-special-operations-wing] McNamara actively began to consider dispatching United States military forces to test the utility of counterinsurgency techniques in Southeast Asia.
[src:helicopter/1st-special-operations-wing] In response, Air Force Chief of Staff General Curtis LeMay pointed out that the 4400th was operationally ready and could serve as an Air Force contingent for that force.
[src:helicopter/1st-special-operations-wing] Kennedy directed, in NSAM 104, that the Defense Secretary "introduce the Air Force 'Jungle Jim' Squadron into South Vietnam for the initial purpose of training Vietnamese forces." The 4400th was to proceed as a training mission and not for combat at the present time.
[src:helicopter/1st-special-operations-wing] "Jungle Jim" was a code name and nickname of the original 4400th CCTS and Air Commandos.
[src:helicopter/1st-special-operations-wing] Members wore an Australian-type green fatigue slouch hat in the style Johnny Weissmuller wore in the *Jungle Jim* films.
[src:helicopter/1st-special-operations-wing] The commandos were to maintain a low profile in-country and avoid the press.
[src:helicopter/1st-special-operations-wing] The aircraft were painted with Republic of Vietnam Air Force (RVNAF) insignia, and all pilots wore plain flight suits minus all insignia and name tags that could identify them as Americans.
[src:helicopter/1st-special-operations-wing] They also sanitized their wallets and did not carry Geneva Convention cards.
[src:helicopter/1st-special-operations-wing] Those Air Commandos who served with the Raven Forward Air Controllers in the Secret War in Laos from 1966 to 1974 would continue this sanitized routine during their service there.
[src:helicopter/1st-special-operations-wing] Elevated to group level as 4440th Combat Crew Training Group, 20 March 1962.
[src:helicopter/1st-special-operations-wing] The provisional TAC group was replaced by AFCON **1st Air Commando Wing** in Apr 1962 and assumed air commando operations and training responsibility.
[src:helicopter/1st-special-operations-wing] Trained United States and RVNAF aircrews in the United States and South Vietnam in unconventional warfare, counter-insurgency, psychological warfare, and civic actions throughout the Vietnam War.
[src:helicopter/1st-special-operations-wing] Elements of the wing participated in the Operation Eagle Claw attempt in April 1980 to rescue U.S. hostages held in Tehran, Iran.
[src:helicopter/1st-special-operations-wing] Thereafter, continued to work closely with multi-service special operations forces to develop combat tactics for numerous types of aircraft and conduct combat crew training for USAF and foreign aircrews.
[src:helicopter/1st-special-operations-wing] Conducted numerous disaster relief; search and rescue; medical evacuation; and humanitarian support missions.
[src:helicopter/1st-special-operations-wing] A notable rescue operation they participated in was the rescue of tourists from the roof of their 26 story hotel during the 1980 MGM Grand fire in Las Vegas.
[src:helicopter/1st-special-operations-wing] Part of the unit was participating in the yearly Exercise Red Flag at Nellis AFB when the call came from local authorities that several hundred people were trapped on the roof of the enflamed MGM.
[src:helicopter/1st-special-operations-wing] It took several local and military helicopters several hours flying in dangerous conditions to rescue as many people as they could.
[src:helicopter/1st-special-operations-wing] Supported drug interdiction efforts in a coordinated program involving multiple US and foreign agencies, 1983–1985.
[src:helicopter/1st-special-operations-wing] Beginning in August 1990, the wing deployed personnel and equipment to Saudi Arabia for Operation Desert Shield/Storm.
[src:helicopter/1st-special-operations-wing] These forces carried out combat search and rescue, unconventional warfare, and direct strike missions during the war, including suppression of Iraqi forces during the Battle of Khafji, January 1991.
[src:helicopter/1st-special-operations-wing] Deployed personnel and equipment worldwide, performing combat search and rescue, and supporting contingencies, humanitarian relief, and exercises that included Bosnia-Herzegovina, Iraq, Kuwait, and Central America.
[src:helicopter/1st-special-operations-wing] Elements of the wing deployed to participate in Operation Provide Comfort in Iraq, 1991 to 1996 and Operation Deny Flight, Bosnia-Herzegovina, 1993 to 1995.
[src:helicopter/1st-special-operations-wing] It supported Operation Deliberate Force/Joint Endeavor, August to September 1995 and 14 to 20 December 1996, flying combat missions and attacking targets critical to Bosnian-Serb Army operations.
[src:helicopter/1st-special-operations-wing] Wing elements participated in operations Northern and Southern Watch in 1997 and again participated in combat operations in Desert Thunder, February to June 1998 and Desert Fox, 17 to 21 December 1998.
[src:helicopter/1st-special-operations-wing] It assumed an additional mission, supporting the Aerospace Expeditionary Forces in February 2000.
[src:helicopter/1st-special-operations-wing] After the 11 September 2001 terrorist attacks.
[src:helicopter/1st-special-operations-wing] Sikorsky MH-53 "Pave Lows" responded almost immediately to support relief efforts in New York City and Washington, D.C.
[src:helicopter/1st-special-operations-wing] In 2001 and 2002 the wing deployed elements to Afghanistan and Iraq and fought in other "war on terror" operations.
[src:helicopter/1st-special-operations-wing] The 1st SOW mission focus is unconventional warfare: counter-terrorism, combat search and rescue, personnel recovery, psychological operations, aviation assistance to developing nations, "deep battlefield" resupply, interdiction and close air support.
[src:helicopter/1st-special-operations-wing] The wing has units located at Hurlburt Field, Florida, Eglin Air Force Base, Florida, and Nellis Air Force Base, Nevada.
[src:helicopter/1st-special-operations-wing] The wing is the pivotal component of AFSOC's ability to provide and conduct missions ranging from precision application of firepower to infiltration, exfiltration, resupply and refueling of special operations force operational elements.
[src:helicopter/1st-special-operations-wing] In addition, the 1st SOW brings distinctive intelligence capabilities to the fight, including intelligence, surveillance and reconnaissance contributions, predictive analysis, and targeting expertise to joint special operations forces and combat search and rescue operations.
[src:helicopter/1st-special-operations-wing] Since the United States invasion of Afghanistan began in October 2001, the wing's aircraft have flown more than 25,000 combat sorties, amassing more than 75,000 combat hours.
[src:helicopter/1st-special-operations-wing] The wing has also deployed more than 8,500 personnel to 16 geographic locations around the world.
[src:helicopter/2002-khankala-mi-26-crash] On 19 August 2002, a group of Chechen fighters armed with a man-portable air-defense system brought down a Russian Mil Mi-26 helicopter in a minefield, which resulted in the death of 127 Russian soldiers in the greatest loss of life in the history of helicopter aviation.
[src:helicopter/2002-khankala-mi-26-crash] It is also the deadliest aviation disaster ever suffered by the Russian Armed Forces.
[src:helicopter/2002-khankala-mi-26-crash] The helicopter was ferrying 142 soldiers and officers belonging to various units, mostly from the 20th Guards Motor Rifle Division, from the Russian Air Force base at Mozdok, Republic of North Ossetia–Alania.
[src:helicopter/2002-khankala-mi-26-crash] The interior of the helicopter flooded with fuel and its jammed doors could not be opened.
[src:helicopter/2002-khankala-mi-26-crash] Only the crew of five and 29 passengers managed to escape through the small cockpit exit hatch.
[src:helicopter/2002-khankala-mi-26-crash] Fourteen of the survivors died over the next few days from severe burns.
[src:helicopter/2002-khankala-mi-26-crash] Russian forces from Khankala launched a search for the attackers immediately after the crash, but only managed to recover the spent tube that had contained the Igla missile.
[src:helicopter/2002-khankala-mi-26-crash] On 21 August 2002, a national day of mourning was declared for the following day by Russian President Vladimir Putin in connection with the catastrophe, which the media called "the second *Kursk*".
[src:helicopter/2002-khankala-mi-26-crash] The separatist news agency Kavkaz Center described the crash as the "greatest act of sabotage by Chechen fighters in two years".
[src:helicopter/2002-khankala-mi-26-crash] Some Russian media, including *Izvestiya*, voiced anger at an apparent cover-up attempt, accusing the military of "as usual" trying to conceal the casualties.
[src:helicopter/2002-khankala-mi-26-crash] The crash led to the suspension of the Russian army's Aviation commander, Colonel-General Vitaly Pavlov, who later resigned from his post in September.
[src:helicopter/2002-khankala-mi-26-crash] The regimental commander of the 487th, Lieutenant Colonel Anatoly Kudyakov, was convicted of negligence of allowing the helicopter to be overloaded but ultimately acquitted of the charges.
[src:helicopter/2002-khankala-mi-26-crash] On 24 September, footage of the helicopter downing was obtained by the Associated Press from a Turkish news agency along with a statement by separatist Chechen President Aslan Maskhadov announcing: "Here is a helicopter that is on fire and falling near Khankala.
[src:helicopter/2002-khankala-mi-26-crash] It was hit by our Igla anti-aircraft missile." It was also the first video that showed Maskhadov using Islamic insignia and flag, instead of Chechen ones, and referring to the fighters around him as "our mujahideen", in what was seen as his apparent and abrupt turn towards Islamism.
[src:helicopter/2002-khankala-mi-26-crash] In an undated tape, Maskhadov recalls the Russian investigators' early official version that the helicopter crashed because of technical difficulties before announcing that it was shot down; he then presents a handgun to the fighter said to have downed the helicopter.
[src:helicopter/2002-khankala-mi-26-crash] The tape was also aired on television in Chechnya when the separatists used the REN TV frequency to broadcast it locally during that same month.
[src:helicopter/2002-khankala-mi-26-crash] It was believed that the missile that destroyed the helicopter was launched from one of the many battle-damaged five-story apartment blocks on the outskirts of Grozny.
[src:helicopter/2002-khankala-mi-26-crash] The Russian military responded to the loss of the Mi-26 by demolishing several blocks in the already half-destroyed Khankala residential area adjoining the base in November, in spite of protests from the pro-Russian Chechen administration.
[src:helicopter/2002-khankala-mi-26-crash] It was initially flatly denied by Colonel Boris Podoprigora, but later admitted by the Russian military spokesman Major-General Ilya Shabalkin, who said that the action was carried out with the goal of preventing the fighters from using the area to lay ambushes close to the base.
[src:helicopter/2002-khankala-mi-26-crash] As a result, around 100 families were left homeless and NTV reported they were given barely any time to leave and could take only some personal belongings.
[src:helicopter/2002-khankala-mi-26-crash] Regarding this, General Shabalkin commented that the local residents "had been watching the bandits preparing terror attacks and failed to inform law enforcers of their plans" which "is considered to be abetting illegal armed formations, and complicity in a criminal plot".
[src:helicopter/2002-khankala-mi-26-crash] In response, the Russian State Duma deputy for Chechnya, Aslambek Aslakhanov, demanded an explanation from the top military command in Chechnya.
[src:helicopter/2002-khankala-mi-26-crash] The area had been also shelled in August following an unrelated crash of a Mil Mi-8 helicopter carrying two high-ranking Russian military officials, killing everyone on board, which was allegedly caused by a missile launched from the Oktyabrsky district of Grozny.
[src:helicopter/2002-khankala-mi-26-crash] The Mi-26 helicopter was designed to carry 80 troops, while the one that was destroyed was loaded with 142 passengers (according to Timur Aliyev, "an indication in itself that the Russian military is reluctant to travel by road, even in areas like northern Chechnya far from the rebel heartlands").
[src:helicopter/2002-khankala-mi-26-crash] *Pravda* commented that he "had to become a scapegoat" and according to Kudyakov himself the judge told him that he should have refused to go to Chechnya in the first place.
[src:helicopter/2002-khankala-mi-26-crash] A Chechen accused of transporting the missile, preparing it for launching, and filming the attack, 27-year-old Grozny resident Doku Dzhantemirov, was found guilty of planning and carrying out "an act of terror" in April 2004.
[src:helicopter/2002-khankala-mi-26-crash] He was sentenced to life imprisonment for "terrorism, premeditated murder with special cruelty, banditry, and attempted murder of servicemen", and was also ordered to pay 100,000 rubles ($3,500) to the relatives of each victim and 50,000 rubles ($1,720) to each of the survivors.
[src:helicopter/2002-khankala-mi-26-crash] At his trial, Dzhantemirov maintained that he was not a terrorist but a soldier of the state of Ichkeria.
[src:helicopter/2002-khankala-mi-26-crash] Four other Chechens accused of taking part in the attack were still being sought.
[src:helicopter/2005-al-anbar-ch-53e-crash] The **2005 Al-Anbar CH-53E crash** refers to an aviation accident which occurred on January 26, 2005 when a United States Marine Corps CH-53E Super Stallion helicopter crashed while ferrying U.S. military personnel in the Al-Anbar province of western Iraq, near the town of Ar-Rutbah.
[src:helicopter/2005-al-anbar-ch-53e-crash] All thirty-one troops aboard the helicopter died in the crash, which made it the deadliest single incident for U.S. troops during the Iraq War.
[src:helicopter/2005-al-anbar-ch-53e-crash] The accident took place while coalition forces were trying to secure the country ahead of the January 2005 Iraqi parliamentary election slated to take place later that month.
[src:helicopter/2005-al-anbar-ch-53e-crash] The cause of the crash was determined to be the pilots becoming disoriented when they flew into a sandstorm.
[src:helicopter/2005-al-anbar-ch-53e-crash] The CH-53E Super Stallion first entered service in 1981, becoming the largest and heaviest helicopter in the inventory of the United States military.
[src:helicopter/2005-al-anbar-ch-53e-crash] Its three gas turbine engines gave the helicopter a superior amount of thrust capability and allowed it to become the workhorse of the U.S.
[src:helicopter/2005-al-anbar-ch-53e-crash] U.S. forces in Iraq were also at the time facing increasing opposition to its previously unchallenged air superiority.
[src:helicopter/2005-al-anbar-ch-53e-crash] Insurgent forces were increasingly targeting coalition aircraft, usually American helicopters, which provided ample targets.
[src:helicopter/2005-al-anbar-ch-53e-crash] In November 2003, a CH-47 Chinook helicopter was shot down near Fallujah by a shoulder-fired missile, killing 16 American troops.
[src:helicopter/2005-al-anbar-ch-53e-crash] In 2004, a total of 13 U.S. helicopters were brought down by enemy ground fire over Iraq.
[src:helicopter/2005-al-anbar-ch-53e-crash] The increasing prevalence of ground fire led American forces to change their tactics, and helicopters began flying low and predominantly at night to avoid drawing fire.
[src:helicopter/2005-al-anbar-ch-53e-crash] Another threat to U.S. helicopters in Iraq was sand.
[src:helicopter/2005-al-anbar-ch-53e-crash] The arid desert environment led many U.S. aircraft to become contaminated with large quantities of sand, affecting aircraft performance and overall mechanical well-being as well as posing a threat to pilots, who can be blinded during landing operations.
[src:helicopter/2005-al-anbar-ch-53e-crash] At an October 2003 hearing of the House Armed Services Committee, Representative Joel Hefley (R-CO), the chairman, said the typical Super Stallion returning from service in Afghanistan and Iraq was found to have 150 pounds of sand spread throughout its interior.
[src:helicopter/2005-al-anbar-ch-53e-crash] At 1:20 am AST on 26 January 2005 a CH-53E Super Stallion helicopter (164536), code named Sampson 22 from Marine Heavy Helicopter Squadron 361 (HMH-361) was ferrying a platoon of U.S.
[src:helicopter/2005-al-anbar-ch-53e-crash] Marines from the 3rd Marine Division in Al-Anbar province, Iraq near the town of Ar-Rutbah, about seventy miles from the Jordanian border when it encountered a sandstorm.
[src:helicopter/2005-al-anbar-ch-53e-crash] Gordon, 31, became disoriented in the storm and did not realize the helicopter was banking to the left when it crashed into the ground.
[src:helicopter/2005-al-anbar-ch-53e-crash] All of the four crew and 27 passengers, of which all but one were U.S.
[src:helicopter/2005-al-anbar-ch-53e-crash] General John Abizaid, commander of US troops in Iraq, said the helicopter was on "a routine mission in support of the elections".
[src:helicopter/2005-al-anbar-ch-53e-crash] The helicopter was carrying the troops to secure a polling site in preparation for the January 2005 Iraqi parliamentary elections set to take place four days from the day of the crash.
[src:helicopter/2005-al-anbar-ch-53e-crash] At 10:00 a.m the same day of the crash, the Marines confirmed the loss of all thirty-one aboard the helicopter.
[src:helicopter/2005-al-anbar-ch-53e-crash] The helicopter crash was the deadliest loss of American troops in a single incident of the entire Iraq War, and as a result January 26, 2005, became the deadliest day for U.S. troops during the war, since six more American troops were killed throughout the country on that day.
[src:helicopter/2005-al-anbar-ch-53e-crash] Day, the mishap CH-53E's wingman, was relieved of flying duty as a result of the crash and faced the threat of charges of dereliction of duty after it was revealed that he was responsible for providing updated weather information for the flight.
[src:helicopter/2005-al-anbar-ch-53e-crash] A heavily redacted 400-page report cited causes such as spatial disorientation, overconfidence in the use of night-vision goggles, and pilot error in addition to the poor weather conditions.
[src:helicopter/2005-al-anbar-ch-53e-crash] In a statement on January 26, President George W.
[src:helicopter/2005-al-anbar-ch-53e-crash] Bush paid condolences to the men killed in the crash in a larger statement about the Iraqi elections stating "The story today is going to be very discouraging to the American people," Bush said at the White House.
[src:helicopter/2005-al-anbar-ch-53e-crash] And we weep and mourn when soldiers lose their life.
[src:helicopter/2005-al-anbar-ch-53e-crash] And—but it is the long-term objective that is vital, and that is to spread freedom.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] A **helicopter** is a type of rotorcraft in which lift and thrust are supplied by horizontally spinning rotors.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] This allows the helicopter to take off and land vertically, to hover, and to fly forward, backward and laterally.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] These attributes allow helicopters to be used in congested or isolated areas where fixed-wing aircraft and many forms of short take-off and landing (STOL) or short take-off and vertical landing (STOVL) aircraft cannot perform without a runway.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] The Focke-Wulf Fw 61 was the first successful, practical, and fully controllable helicopter in 1936, while in 1942, the Sikorsky R-4 became the first helicopter to reach full-scale production.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] Starting in 1939 and through 1943, Igor Sikorsky worked on the development of the VS-300, which over four iterations, became the basis for modern helicopters with a single main rotor and a single tail rotor.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] Although most earlier designs used more than one main rotor, the configuration of a single main rotor accompanied by a vertical anti-torque tail rotor (i.e.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] *unicopter*, not to be confused with the single-blade monocopter) has become the most common helicopter configuration.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] However, twin-rotor helicopters (bicopters), in either tandem or transverse rotors configurations, are sometimes in use due to their greater payload capacity than the monorotor design, and coaxial-rotor, tiltrotor and compound helicopters are also all flying today.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] The English word *helicopter* is adapted from the French word *hélicoptère*, coined by Gustave Ponton d'Amécourt in 1861, which is composed of the Ancient Greek roots **helix** (ἕλιξ, *genitive* *helikos* (ἕλῐκος), "helix, spiral, whirl, convolution"), and **pteron** (πτερόν, "wing").
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] The word is often (erroneously, from an etymological point of view) rebracketed by English speakers as consisting of *heli-* and *-copter*, leading to words like *helipad* and *quadcopter*.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] English language nicknames for "helicopter" include "chopper", "copter", "heli", and "whirlybird".
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] In the United States military, a common military slang term used is "helo" (pronounced /ˈhiː.loʊ/).
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] A helicopter is a type of rotorcraft in which lift and thrust are supplied by one or more horizontally-spinning rotors.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] By contrast the autogyro (or gyroplane) and gyrodyne have a free-spinning rotor for all or part of the flight envelope, relying on a separate thrust system to propel the craft forwards, so that the airflow sets the rotor spinning to provide lift.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] The compound helicopter also has a separate thrust system, but continues to supply power to the rotor throughout normal flight.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] U.S. federal regulations state that "helicopter" means a rotorcraft that, for its horizontal motion, depends principally on its engine-driven rotors.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] The rotor system, or more simply *rotor*, is the rotating part of a helicopter that generates lift.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] A rotor system may be mounted horizontally, as main rotors are, providing lift vertically, or it may be mounted vertically, such as a tail rotor, to provide horizontal thrust to counteract torque from the main rotors.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] The rotor consists of a mast, hub and rotor blades.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] The mast is a cylindrical metal shaft that extends upwards from the transmission.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] At the top of the mast is the attachment point for the rotor blades called the hub.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] Main rotor systems are classified according to how the rotor blades are attached and move relative to the hub.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] There are three basic types: hingeless, fully articulated, and teetering; although some modern rotor systems use a combination of these.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] Most helicopters have a single main rotor, but torque created by its aerodynamic drag must be countered by an opposed torque.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] The design that Igor Sikorsky settled on for his VS-300 was a smaller tail rotor.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] The tail rotor pushes or pulls against the tail to counter the torque effect, and this has become the most common configuration for helicopter design, usually at the end of a *tail boom*.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] Some helicopters use other anti-torque controls instead of the tail rotor, such as the ducted fan (called *Fenestron* or *FANTAIL*) and NOTAR.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] NOTAR provides anti-torque similar to the way a wing develops lift through the use of the Coandă effect on the tail boom.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] The use of two or more horizontal rotors turning in opposite directions is another configuration used to counteract the effects of torque on the aircraft without relying on an anti-torque tail rotor.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] This allows the power normally required to be diverted for the tail rotor to be applied fully to the main rotors, increasing the aircraft's power efficiency and lifting capacity.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] Tip jet designs let the rotor push itself through the air and avoid generating torque.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] The number, size and type of engine(s) used on a helicopter determines the size, function and capability of that helicopter design.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] The earliest helicopter engines were simple mechanical devices, such as rubber bands or spindles, which relegated the size of helicopters to toys and small models.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] For a half century before the first airplane flight, steam engines were used to forward the development of the understanding of helicopter aerodynamics, but the limited power did not allow for manned flight.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] The introduction of the internal combustion engine at the end of the 19th century became the watershed for helicopter development as engines began to be developed and produced that were powerful enough to allow for helicopters able to lift humans.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] Early helicopter designs utilized custom-built engines or rotary engines designed for airplanes, but these were soon replaced by more powerful automobile engines and radial engines.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] The single, most-limiting factor of helicopter development during the first half of the 20th century was that the amount of power produced by an engine was not able to overcome the engine's weight in vertical flight.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] This was overcome in early successful helicopters by using the smallest engines available.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] When the compact, flat engine was developed, the helicopter industry found a lighter-weight powerplant easily adapted to small helicopters, although radial engines continued to be used for larger helicopters.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] Turbine engines revolutionized the aviation industry; and the turboshaft engine for helicopter use, pioneered in December 1951 by the aforementioned Kaman K-225, finally gave helicopters an engine with a large amount of power and a low weight penalty.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] Turboshafts are also more reliable than piston engines, especially when producing the sustained high levels of power required by a helicopter.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] The turboshaft engine was able to be scaled to the size of the helicopter being designed, so that all but the lightest of helicopter models are powered by turbine engines today.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] Special jet engines developed to drive the rotor from the rotor tips are referred to as tip jets.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] Tip jets powered by a remote compressor are referred to as cold tip jets, while those powered by combustion exhaust are referred to as hot tip jets.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] An example of a cold jet helicopter is the Sud-Ouest Djinn, and an example of the hot tip jet helicopter is the YH-32 Hornet.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] Some radio-controlled helicopters and smaller, helicopter-type unmanned aerial vehicles, use electric motors or motorcycle engines.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] Radio-controlled helicopters may also have piston engines that use fuels other than gasoline, such as nitromethane.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] Some turbine engines commonly used in helicopters can also use biodiesel instead of jet fuel.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] There are also human-powered helicopters.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] The transmission is a mechanical system that transmits power from the engine(s) to the rotors.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] For helicopters with tail rotors, the transmission drivetrain forks into two paths: one leading to the main rotor, and one leading to the tail rotor.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] The drive shafts of helicopter engines are typically not aligned with the rotor shafts, so the transmission must translate the alignment of the drive shaft to match the shafts of the rotors.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] Many engine drive shafts are aligned horizontally, yet the main rotor shaft ("mast") is usually vertical, and the tail rotor shaft is often perpendicular to the engine's drive shaft.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] The transmission contains a series of gears, usually bevel gears, that translate the alignment of the drive shaft to the alignment of the rotor shafts.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] The transmission also reduces the RPMs of the engine to the lower RPMs required by the rotors.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] The output drive shaft of the engine, before any gearing is applied, is typically between 3,000 and 50,000 RPM (turbine engines typically have higher RPM than piston engines).
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] The main rotor typically rotates between 300 and 600 RPM.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] The tail rotor, if present, usually rotates between 1,000 and 5,000 RPM.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] (The RPMs of a given model of helicopter are usually fixed — the RPM ranges listed above represent a variety of helicopter models).
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] The transmission contains a series of reduction gears to reduce the engine RPM to the rotor RPMs.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] Several types of reduction gears may be used, including bevel gears, planetary gears, helical gears, and spur gears.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] The transmission often includes one or more clutches, which permit the rotors to engage or disengage from the engine.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] A clutch is required so the engine can start up and gain speed before taking the load of the rotors.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] A clutch is also required in the case of engine failure: in that situation, the rotors must disengage from the engine so that the rotors can continue spinning and perform autorotation.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] Helicopter clutches are usually freewheel clutches relying on centrifugal forces (sprag clutchs are commonly used), but belt drive clutches are also used.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] A helicopter has four flight control inputs.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] These are the cyclic, the collective, the anti-torque foot pedals, and the throttle.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] The cyclic control is usually located between the pilot's legs and is commonly called the *cyclic stick* or just *cyclic* or *stick* and moves forwards and backwards and side to side.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] On most helicopters, the cyclic is similar to a joystick.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] However, the Robinson R22, Robinson R44 and Robinson R66 have a unique teetering-bar cyclic control system and a few helicopters have a cyclic control that descends into the cockpit from overhead.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] The cyclic is called the cyclic because it cyclically changes the pitch of the main rotor blades.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] In a forward flight state, as the blades rotate, the blade rotating forward will see higher speed and a corresponding increase in lift compared to the retreating blade.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] As such, the angle of attack of the forward rotating blade has to be lower than the retreating blade or the helicopter will roll to the retreating blade side.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] This happens cyclically as the blades rotate through a complete rotation leading to the naming of this control as the cyclic.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] The cyclic controls this differential angle.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] The cyclic controls the tilt of the rotor.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] In hover, the cyclic controls motion of the helicopter over the ground.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] In flight, the cyclic controls the pitch and roll of the helicopter.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] In a hover, if the pilot pushes the cyclic forward, the rotor disk tilts forward, and the rotor produces a thrust in the forward direction.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] If the pilot pushes the cyclic to the side, the rotor disk tilts to that side and produces thrust in that direction, causing the helicopter to move sideways.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] Because of precession, the cyclic moves the swashplate 90 degrees before the desired main rotor tilt.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] This can be seen when the rotor is stopped.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] With the blades aligned fore/aft, moving the cyclic forward does not change the blade angle but moving the cyclic to the side will change the blade angle.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] In flight, the cyclic acts like the stick in an airplane.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] Moving the cyclic forward pitches the nose down for more speed.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] Moving the cyclic aft lifts the nose to slow the aircraft.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] Moving the cyclic to the side rolls the helicopter in that direction which generally leads to turning in that direction, assuming coordinated flight.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] The collective pitch control or *collective* is located on the left side of the pilot's seat with an adjustable friction control to prevent inadvertent movement freeing the pilot's left hand for other uses.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] The collective changes the pitch angle of all the main rotor blades collectively (i.e. all at the same time) and independently of their rotational position.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] Therefore, if an up collective input is made, all the blades increase angle of attack equally, and the result is additional lift (power) to the main rotor system which can increase helicopter speed or altitude.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] Lowering the collective results in less lift from the main rotor system.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] A swashplate controls the collective and cyclic pitch of the main blades.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] The swashplate moves up and down, along the main shaft, to change the pitch of the blades.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] The stick is connected to the swash plate through the collective and cyclic systems allowing both systems to independently control the angle of the blades.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] The anti-torque pedals are located in the same position as the rudder pedals in a fixed-wing aircraft, and serve a similar purpose, namely to control the yaw or direction in which the nose of the aircraft is pointed.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] Application of the pedal in a given direction changes the pitch of the tail rotor blades, increasing or reducing the thrust produced by the tail rotor and causing the nose to yaw in the direction of the applied pedal.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] The pedals mechanically change the pitch of the tail rotor altering the amount of thrust produced.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] Helicopters do not exhibit adverse yaw as seen in airplanes and the pedals are not generally required when turning in forward flight.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] Use of the pedals is closely related to the collective in hover.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] For example, increasing collective increases aerodynamic drag on the main rotor system causing a yaw of the helicopter.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] The pedals are used to counter that yaw.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] Both the cyclic and collective can have a wide variety of toggles and switches available to the pilot to control such things as aerodynamic trim, engine speed trim, radio and intercom, hook release, water release, etc.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] This allows the pilot to control these functions without removing their hands from the controls.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] Helicopter rotors are designed to operate in a narrow range of RPM.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] The throttle controls the power produced by the engine, which is connected to the rotor by a fixed ratio transmission.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] The purpose of the throttle is to maintain enough engine power to keep the rotor RPM within allowable limits so that the rotor produces enough lift for flight.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] The throttle control is a motorcycle-style twist grip mounted on the collective control.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] A compound helicopter has an additional system for thrust and, typically, small stub fixed wings.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] This offloads the rotor in cruise, which allows its rotation to be slowed down, thus increasing the maximum speed of the aircraft.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] The Lockheed AH-56A Cheyenne diverted up to 90% of its engine power to a pusher propeller during forward flight.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] There are three basic flight conditions for a helicopter: hover, forward flight and the transition between the two.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] Hovering is the most challenging part of flying a helicopter.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] Required are constant control inputs and corrections by the pilot to keep the helicopter where it is required to be.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] Despite the complexity of the task, the control inputs in a hover are simple.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] The cyclic is used to eliminate drift in the horizontal plane, that is to control forward and back, right and left.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] The collective is used to maintain altitude.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] The pedals are used to control nose direction or heading.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] It is the interaction of these controls that makes hovering so difficult, since an adjustment in any one control requires an adjustment of the other two, creating a cycle of constant correction.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] In addition, the center of lift of the main rotor system is significantly above the center of gravity (CG) of the helicopter.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] Thus, any lateral perturbation of the helicopter in a hover will tend to increase as the rotor lift will increasingly roll or pitch the helicopter in a positive-feedback rotor-lift versus helicopter CG situation.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] The lateral motion of the helicopter lags behind the roll induced by the rotor lift side vector which will lead an inexperienced pilot into a pilot induced oscillation (PIO) and eventual loss of control.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] A hovering helicopter is surrounded by a vortex of air pushing the helicopter down.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] This can be a hover in ground effect or out of ground effect.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] Thus, when in a hover, the engine needs to provide enough power to both counter helicopter weight as well as counter this downward flow of air into the rotor system.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] As a helicopter moves from hover to forward flight it flies out of this downward flowing vortex and enters a state called translational lift which provides extra lift without increasing power.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] This state, most typically, occurs when the airspeed reaches approximately 16–24 knots (30–44 km/h; 18–28 mph), and may be necessary for a helicopter to obtain flight.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] A maneuver called a running take off involves sliding the helicopter on the ground at increasing speed until sufficient lift is achieved for flight.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] In forward flight a helicopter's flight controls behave more like those of a fixed-wing aircraft.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] Applying forward pressure on the cyclic will cause the nose to pitch down, with a resultant increase in airspeed and loss of altitude.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] Aft cyclic will cause the nose to pitch up, slowing the helicopter and causing it to climb.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] Increasing collective (power) while maintaining a constant airspeed will induce a climb while decreasing collective will cause a descent.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] Coordinating these two inputs, down collective plus aft cyclic or up collective plus forward cyclic, will result in airspeed changes while maintaining a constant altitude.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] Helicopters do not exhibit adverse yaw and the pedals are not generally needed for forward flight, even when turning.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] If the engine fails or is disconnected from the rotor system, the helicopter will enter an autorotation, where the helicopter's main rotor turns due to air moving up through the rotor, instead of engine power driving the rotor.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] Today, helicopter uses include transportation of people and cargo, military uses, construction, firefighting, search and rescue, tourism, medical transport, law enforcement, agriculture, news and media, and aerial observation, among others.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] A helicopter used to carry loads connected to long cables or slings is called an aerial crane.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] Aerial cranes are used to place heavy equipment, like radio transmission towers and large air conditioning units, on the tops of tall buildings, or when an item must be raised up in a remote area, such as a radio tower raised on the top of a hill or mountain.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] Helicopters are used as aerial cranes in the logging industry to lift trees out of terrain where vehicles cannot travel and where environmental concerns prohibit the building of roads.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] These operations are referred to as longline because of the long, single sling line used to carry the load.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] In military service helicopters are often useful for delivery of outsized slung loads that would not fit inside ordinary cargo aircraft: artillery pieces, large machinery (field radars, communications gear, electrical generators), or pallets of bulk cargo.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] In military operations these payloads are often delivered to remote locations made inaccessible by mountainous or riverine terrain, or naval vessels at sea.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] In electronic news gathering, helicopters have provided aerial views of some major news stories, and have been doing so, from the late 1960s.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] Helicopters have also been used in films, both in front and behind the camera.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] The largest single non-combat helicopter operation in history was the disaster management operation following the 1986 Chernobyl nuclear disaster.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] Hundreds of pilots were involved in airdrop and observation missions, making dozens of sorties a day for several months.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] "Helitack" is the use of helicopters to combat wildland fires.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] The helicopters are used for aerial firefighting (water bombing) and may be fitted with tanks or carry helibuckets.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] Helibuckets, such as the Bambi bucket, are usually filled by submerging the bucket into lakes, rivers, reservoirs, or portable tanks.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] Tanks fitted onto helicopters are filled from a hose while the helicopter is on the ground or water is siphoned from lakes or reservoirs through a hanging snorkel as the helicopter hovers over the water source.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] Helitack helicopters are also used to deliver firefighters, who rappel down to inaccessible areas, and to resupply firefighters.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] Common firefighting helicopters include variants of the Bell 205 and the Erickson S-64 Aircrane helitanker.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] Helicopters are used as air ambulances for emergency medical assistance in situations when an ambulance cannot easily or quickly reach the scene, or cannot transport the patient to a medical facility in time.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] Helicopters are also used when patients need to be transported between medical facilities and air transportation is the most practical method.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] An air ambulance helicopter is equipped to stabilize and provide limited medical treatment to a patient while in flight.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] The use of helicopters as air ambulances is often referred to as "MEDEVAC", and patients are referred to as being "airlifted", or "medevaced".
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] This use was pioneered in the Korean War, when time to reach a medical facility was reduced to three hours from the eight hours needed in World War II, and further reduced to two hours by the Vietnam War.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] In naval service a prime function of rescue helicopters is to promptly retrieve downed aircrew involved in crashes occurring upon launch or recovery aboard aircraft carriers.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] In past years this function was performed by destroyers escorting the carrier, but since then helicopters have proved vastly more effective.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] Police departments and other law enforcement agencies use helicopters to pursue suspects and patrol the skies.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] Since helicopters can achieve a unique aerial view, they are often used in conjunction with police on the ground to report on suspects' locations and movements.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] They are often mounted with lighting and heat-sensing equipment for night pursuits.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] Military forces use attack helicopters to conduct aerial attacks on ground targets.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] Such helicopters are mounted with missile launchers and miniguns.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] Transport helicopters are used to ferry troops and supplies where the lack of an airstrip would make transport via fixed-wing aircraft impossible.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] The use of transport helicopters to deliver troops as an attack force on an objective is referred to as "air assault".
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] Unmanned aerial systems (UAS) helicopter systems of varying sizes are developed by companies for military reconnaissance and surveillance duties.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] Naval forces also use helicopters equipped with dipping sonar for anti-submarine warfare, since they can operate from small ships.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] Oil companies charter helicopters to move workers and parts quickly to remote drilling sites located at sea or in remote locations.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] The speed advantage over boats makes the high operating cost of helicopters cost-effective in ensuring that oil platforms continue to operate.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] Various companies specialize in this type of operation.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] NASA developed *Ingenuity*, a 1.8 kg (4.0 lb) helicopter used to survey Mars (along with a rover).
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] It began service in February 2021 and was retired due to sustained rotor blade damage in January 2024 after 73 sorties.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] As the Martian atmosphere is 100 times thinner than Earth's, its two blades spin at close to 3,000 revolutions a minute, approximately 10 times faster than that of a terrestrial helicopter.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] In 2017, 926 civil helicopters were shipped for $3.68 billion, led by Airbus Helicopters with $1.87 billion for 369 rotorcraft, Leonardo Helicopters with $806 million for 102 (first three-quarters only), Bell Helicopter with $696 million for 132, then Robinson Helicopter with $161 million for 305.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] The most widespread model is the piston Robinson R44 with 5,600, then the H125/AS350 with 3,600 units, followed by the Bell 206 with 3,400.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] Most were in North America with 34.3% then in Europe with 28.0% followed by Asia-Pacific with 18.6%, Latin America with 11.6%, Africa with 5.3% and Middle East with 1.7%.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] The earliest references for vertical flight came from China.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] Since around 400 BC, Chinese children have played with bamboo flying toys (or Chinese top).
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] This bamboo-copter is spun by rolling a stick attached to a rotor.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] The spinning creates lift, and the toy flies when released.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] The 4th-century AD Daoist book *Baopuzi* by Ge Hong (抱朴子 "Master who Embraces Simplicity") reportedly describes some of the ideas inherent to rotary wing aircraft.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] Designs similar to the Chinese helicopter toy appeared in some Renaissance paintings and other works.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] In the 18th and early 19th centuries Western scientists developed flying machines based on the Chinese toy.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] It was not until the early 1480s, when Italian polymath Leonardo da Vinci created a design for a machine that could be described as an "aerial screw", that any recorded advancement was made towards vertical flight.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] His notes suggested that he built small flying models, but there were no indications for any provision to stop the rotor from making the craft rotate.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] As scientific knowledge increased and became more accepted, people continued to pursue the idea of vertical flight.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] In July 1754, Russian Mikhail Lomonosov had developed a small coaxial modeled after the Chinese top but powered by a wound-up spring device and demonstrated it to the Russian Academy of Sciences.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] It was powered by a spring, and was suggested as a method to lift meteorological instruments.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] In 1783, Christian de Launoy, and his mechanic, Bienvenu, used a coaxial version of the Chinese top in a model consisting of contrarotating turkey flight feathers as rotor blades, and in 1784, demonstrated it to the French Academy of Sciences.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] Sir George Cayley, influenced by a childhood fascination with the Chinese flying top, developed a model of feathers, similar to that of Launoy and Bienvenu, but powered by rubber bands.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] By the end of the century, he had progressed to using sheets of tin for rotor blades and springs for power.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] His writings on his experiments and models would become influential on future aviation pioneers.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] Alphonse Pénaud would later develop coaxial rotor model helicopter toys in 1870, also powered by rubber bands.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] One of these toys, given as a gift by their father, would inspire the Wright brothers to pursue the dream of flight.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] In 1861, the word "helicopter" was coined by Gustave de Ponton d'Amécourt, a French inventor who demonstrated a small steam-powered model.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] While celebrated as an innovative use of a new metal, aluminum, the model never lifted off the ground.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] D'Amecourt's linguistic contribution would survive to eventually describe the vertical flight he had envisioned.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] Steam power was popular with other inventors as well.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] In 1877, the Italian engineer, inventor and aeronautical pioneer Enrico Forlanini developed an unmanned helicopter powered by a steam engine.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] It rose to a height of 13 meters (43 feet), where it remained for 20 seconds, after a vertical take-off from a park in Milan.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] Milan has dedicated its city airport to Enrico Forlanini, also named Linate Airport, as well as the nearby park, the Parco Forlanini.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] Emmanuel Dieuaide's steam-powered design featured counter-rotating rotors powered through a hose from a boiler on the ground.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] In 1887 Parisian inventor, Gustave Trouvé, built and flew a tethered electric model helicopter.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] In July 1901, the maiden flight of Hermann Ganswindt's helicopter took place in Berlin-Schöneberg; this was probably the first heavier-than-air motor-driven flight carrying humans.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] A movie covering the event was taken by Max Skladanowsky, but it remains lost.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] In 1885, Thomas Edison was given US$1,000 (equivalent to $36,000 today) by James Gordon Bennett, Jr., to conduct experiments towards developing flight.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] Edison built a helicopter and used the paper for a stock ticker to create guncotton, with which he attempted to power an internal combustion engine.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] The helicopter was damaged by explosions and one of his workers was badly burned.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] Edison reported that it would take a motor with a ratio of three to four pounds per horsepower produced to be successful, based on his experiments.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] Ján Bahýľ, a Slovak inventor, adapted the internal combustion engine to power his helicopter model that reached a height of 0.5 meters (1.6 feet) in 1901.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] On 5 May 1905, his helicopter reached 4 meters (13 feet) in altitude and flew for over 1,500 meters (4,900 feet).
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] In 1908, Edison patented his own design for a helicopter powered by a gasoline engine with box kites attached to a mast by cables for a rotor, but it never flew.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] In 1906, two French brothers, Jacques and Louis Breguet, began experimenting with airfoils for helicopters.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] In 1907, those experiments resulted in the *Gyroplane No.1*, possibly as the earliest known example of a quadcopter.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] Although there is some uncertainty about the date, sometime between 14 August and 29 September 1907, the Gyroplane No.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] 1 lifted its pilot into the air about 0.6 metres (2 ft) for a minute.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] 1 proved to be extremely unsteady and required a man at each corner of the airframe to hold it steady.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] For this reason, the flights of the Gyroplane No.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] 1 are considered to be the first manned flight of a helicopter, but not a free or untethered flight.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] That same year, fellow French inventor Paul Cornu designed and built the Cornu helicopter which used two 6.1-metre (20 ft) counter-rotating rotors driven by a 24 hp (18 kW) Antoinette engine.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] On 13 November 1907, it lifted its inventor to 0.3 metres (1 ft) and remained aloft for 20 seconds.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] Even though this flight did not surpass the flight of the Gyroplane No.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] 1, it was reported to be the first truly free flight with a pilot.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] Cornu's helicopter completed a few more flights and achieved a height of nearly 2.0 metres (6.5 ft), but it proved to be unstable and was abandoned.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] Newton Williams of Derby, Connecticut, and Emile Berliner of Washington, D.C., flew a helicopter "on three occasions" at Berliner's lab in Washington's Brightwood neighborhood.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] In 1911, Slovenian philosopher and economist Ivan Slokar patented a helicopter configuration.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] The Danish inventor Jacob Ellehammer built the Ellehammer helicopter in 1912.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] It consisted of a frame equipped with two counter-rotating discs, each of which was fitted with six vanes around its circumference.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] After indoor tests, the aircraft was demonstrated outdoors and made several free take-offs.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] Experiments with the helicopter continued until September 1916, when it tipped over during take-off, destroying its rotors.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] During World War I, Austria-Hungary developed the PKZ, an experimental helicopter prototype, with two aircraft built.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] In the early 1920s, Argentine Raúl Pateras-Pescara de Castelluccio, while working in Europe, demonstrated one of the first successful applications of cyclic pitch.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] Coaxial, contra-rotating, biplane rotors could be warped to cyclically increase and decrease the lift they produced.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] The rotor hub could also be tilted forward a few degrees, allowing the aircraft to move forward without a separate propeller to push or pull it.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] Pateras-Pescara was also able to demonstrate the principle of autorotation.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] By January 1924, Pescara's helicopter No.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] 1 was tested but was found to be underpowered and could not lift its own weight.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] The British government funded further research by Pescara which resulted in helicopter No.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] 3, powered by a 250-horsepower (190 kW) radial engine which could fly for up to ten minutes.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] In March 1923 *Time* magazine reported Thomas Edison sent George de Bothezat a congratulations for a successful helicopter test flight.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] Edison wrote, "So far as I know, you have produced the first successful helicopter." The helicopter was tested at McCook's Field and remained airborne for 2 minutes and 45 seconds at a height of 15 feet.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] On 14 April 1924, Frenchman Étienne Oehmichen set the first helicopter world record recognized by the *Fédération Aéronautique Internationale* (FAI), flying his quadrotor helicopter 360 meters (1,180 ft).
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] On 18 April 1924, Pescara beat Oemichen's record, flying for a distance of 736 meters (2,415 ft) (nearly 0.80 kilometers or .5 miles) in 4 minutes and 11 seconds (about 13 km/h or 8 mph), maintaining a height of 1.8 meters (6 feet).
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] On 4 May, Oehmichen completed the first one-kilometer (0.62 mi) closed-circuit helicopter flight in 7 minutes 40 seconds with his No.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] In the US, George de Bothezat built the quadrotor helicopter de Bothezat helicopter for the United States Army Air Service but the Army cancelled the program in 1924, and the aircraft was scrapped.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] Albert Gillis von Baumhauer, a Dutch aeronautical engineer, began studying rotorcraft design in 1923.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] His first prototype "flew" ("hopped" and hovered in reality) on 24 September 1925, with Dutch Army-Air arm Captain Floris Albert van Heijst at the controls.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] The controls that van Heijst used were von Baumhauer's inventions, the cyclic and collective.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] Patents were granted to von Baumhauer for his cyclic and collective controls by the British ministry of aviation on 31 January 1927, under patent number 265,272.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] In 1927, Engelbert Zaschka from Germany built a helicopter, equipped with two rotors, in which a gyroscope was used to increase stability and serves as an energy accumulator for a gliding flight to make a landing.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] Zaschka's aircraft, the first helicopter, which ever worked so successfully in miniature, not only rises and descends vertically, but is able to remain stationary at any height.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] In 1928, Hungarian aviation engineer Oszkár Asbóth constructed a helicopter prototype that took off and landed at least 182 times, with a maximum single flight duration of 53 minutes.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] In 1930, the Italian engineer Corradino D'Ascanio built his D'AT3, a coaxial helicopter.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] His relatively large machine had two, two-bladed, counter-rotating rotors.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] Control was achieved by using auxiliary wings or servo-tabs on the trailing edges of the blades, a concept that was later adopted by other helicopter designers, including Bleeker and Kaman.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] Three small propellers mounted to the airframe were used for additional pitch, roll, and yaw control.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] The D'AT3 held modest FAI speed and altitude records for the time, including altitude (18 m or 59 ft), duration (8 minutes 45 seconds) and distance flown (1,078 m or 3,540 ft).
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] Spanish aeronautical engineer and pilot Juan de la Cierva invented the autogyro in the early 1920s, becoming the first practical rotorcraft.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] In 1928, de la Cierva successfully flew an autogyro across the English Channel, from London to Paris.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] In 1934, an autogyro became the first rotorcraft to successfully take off and land on the deck of a ship.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] That same year, the autogyro was employed by the Spanish military during the Asturias revolt, becoming the first military deployment of a rotorcraft.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] Autogyros were also employed in New Jersey and Pennsylvania for delivering mail and newspapers prior to the invention of the helicopter.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] Though lacking true vertical flight capability, work on the autogyro forms the basis for helicopter analysis.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] Powered by two M-2 powerplants, up-rated copies of the Gnome *Monosoupape* 9 Type B-2 100 CV output rotary engine of World War I, the TsAGI 1-EA made several low altitude flights.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] By 14 August 1932, Cheremukhin managed to get the 1-EA up to an unofficial altitude of 605 meters (1,985 feet), shattering d'Ascanio's earlier achievement.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] As the Soviet Union was not yet a member of the FAI, however, Cheremukhin's record remained unrecognized.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] Nicolas Florine, a Russian engineer, built the first twin tandem rotor machine to perform a free flight.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] It flew in Sint-Genesius-Rode, at the *Laboratoire Aérotechnique de Belgique* (now von Karman Institute) in April 1933, and attained an altitude of six meters (20 feet) and an endurance of eight minutes.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] Florine chose a co-rotating configuration because the gyroscopic stability of the rotors would not cancel.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] Therefore, the rotors had to be tilted slightly in opposite directions to counter torque.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] Using hingeless rotors and co-rotation also minimised the stress on the hull.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] At the time, it was one of the most stable helicopters in existence.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] The Bréguet-Dorand *Gyroplane Laboratoire* was built in 1933.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] It was a coaxial helicopter, contra-rotating.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] After many ground tests and an accident, it first took flight on 26 June 1935.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] Within a short time, the aircraft was setting records with pilot Maurice Claisse at the controls.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] On 14 December 1935, he set a record for closed-circuit flight with a 500-meter (1,600-foot) diameter.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] The next year, on 26 September 1936, Claisse set a height record of 158 meters (518 feet).
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] And, finally, on 24 November 1936, he set a flight duration record of one hour, two minutes and 50 seconds over a 44 kilometers (27 miles) closed circuit at 44.7 kilometres per hour (27.8 mph).
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] The aircraft was destroyed in 1943 by an Allied airstrike at Villacoublay airport.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] Young started work on model helicopters in 1928 using converted electric hover motors to drive the rotor head.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] Young invented the stabilizer bar and patented it shortly after.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] A mutual friend introduced Young to Lawrence Dale, who once seeing his work asked him to join the Bell Aircraft company.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] When Young arrived at Bell in 1941, he signed his patent over and began work on the helicopter.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] His budget was US$250,000 (equivalent to $5.5 million today) to build two working helicopters.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] In just six months they completed the first Bell Model 1, which spawned the Bell Model 30, later succeeded by the Bell 47.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] Heinrich Focke at Focke-Wulf had purchased a license from Cierva Autogiro Company, which according to Frank Kingston Smith Sr., included "the fully controllable cyclic/collective pitch hub system".
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] In return, Cierva Autogiro received a cross-license to build the Focke-Achgelis helicopters.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] Focke designed the world's first practical helicopter, the transverse twin-rotor Focke-Wulf Fw 61, which first flew in June 1936.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] It was demonstrated by Hanna Reitsch in February 1938 inside the Deutschlandhalle in Berlin.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] The Fw 61 set a number of FAI records from 1937 to 1939, including: maximum altitude of 3,427 metres (11,243 ft), maximum distance of 230 kilometres (140 mi), and maximum speed of 124 kilometres per hour (77 mph).
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] Autogiro development was now being bypassed by a focus on helicopters.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] During World War II, Nazi Germany used helicopters in small numbers for observation, transport, and medical evacuation.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] The Flettner Fl 282 *Kolibri* synchropter—using the same basic configuration as Anton Flettner's own pioneering Fl 265—was used in the Baltic, Mediterranean, and Aegean Seas.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] The Focke-Achgelis Fa 223 Drache, like the Fw 61, used two transverse rotors, and was the largest rotorcraft of the war.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] Extensive bombing by the Allied forces prevented Germany from producing helicopters in large quantities during the war.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] In the United States, Russian-born engineer Igor Sikorsky and Wynn Laurence LePage competed to produce the U.S. military's first helicopter.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] LePage received the patent rights to develop helicopters patterned after the Fw 61, and built the XR-1 in 1941.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] Meanwhile, Sikorsky settled on a simpler, single-rotor design, the VS-300 of 1939, which turned out to be the first practical single lifting-rotor helicopter design.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] After experimenting with configurations to counteract the torque produced by the single main rotor, Sikorsky settled on a single, smaller rotor mounted on the tail boom.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] Developed from the VS-300, Sikorsky's R-4 of 1942 was the first large-scale mass-produced helicopter, with a production order for 100 aircraft.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] The R-4 was the only Allied helicopter to serve in World War II, used primarily for search and rescue (by the USAAF 1st Air Commando Group) in the Burma campaign; in Alaska; and in other areas with harsh terrain.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] Total production reached 131 helicopters before the R-4 was replaced by other Sikorsky helicopters such as the R-5 and the R-6.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] In all, Sikorsky produced over 400 helicopters before the end of World War II.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] While LePage and Sikorsky built their helicopters for the military, Bell Aircraft hired Arthur Young to help build a helicopter using Young's two-blade teetering rotor design, which used a weighted stabilizer bar placed at a 90° angle to the rotor blades.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] The subsequent Model 30 helicopter of 1943 showed the design's simplicity and ease of use.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] The Model 30 was developed into the Bell 47 of 1945, which became the first helicopter certified for civilian use in the United States (March 1946).
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] Produced in several countries, the Bell 47 was the most popular helicopter model for nearly 30 years.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] This adaptation of the turbine engine provided a large amount of power to Kaman's helicopter with a lower weight penalty than piston engines, with their heavy engine blocks and auxiliary components.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] On 11 December 1951, the Kaman K-225 became the first turbine-powered helicopter in the world.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] Two years later, on 26 March 1954, a modified Navy HTK-1, another Kaman helicopter, became the first twin-turbine helicopter to fly.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] However, it was the Sud Aviation Alouette II that would become the first helicopter to be produced with a turbine-engine.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] Reliable helicopters capable of stable hover flight were developed decades after fixed-wing aircraft.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] This is largely due to higher engine power density requirements than fixed-wing aircraft.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] Improvements in fuels and engines during the first half of the 20th century were a critical factor in helicopter development.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] The availability of lightweight turboshaft engines in the second half of the 20th century led to the development of larger, faster, and higher-performance helicopters.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p01] While smaller and less expensive helicopters still use piston engines, turboshaft engines are the preferred powerplant for helicopters today.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p02] There are several reasons a helicopter cannot fly as fast as a fixed-wing aircraft.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p02] When the helicopter is hovering, the outer tips of the rotor travel at a speed determined by the length of the blade and the rotational speed.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p02] In a moving helicopter, however, the speed of the blades relative to the air depends on the speed of the helicopter as well as on their rotational speed.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p02] The airspeed of the advancing rotor blade is much higher than that of the helicopter itself.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p02] It is possible for this blade to exceed the speed of sound, and thus produce vastly increased drag and vibration.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p02] At the same time, the advancing blade creates more lift traveling forward, the retreating blade produces less lift.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p02] Dual counter-rotating blades prevent this situation due to having two advancing and two retreating blades with balanced forces.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p02] Because the advancing blade has higher airspeed than the retreating blade and generates a dissymmetry of lift, rotor blades are designed to "flap" – lift and twist in such a way that the advancing blade flaps up and develops a smaller angle of attack.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p02] Conversely, the retreating blade flaps down, develops a higher angle of attack, and generates more lift.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p02] At high speeds, the force on the rotors is such that they "flap" excessively, and the retreating blade can reach too high an angle and stall.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p02] For this reason, the maximum safe forward airspeed of a helicopter is given a design rating called VNE, *velocity, never exceed*.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p02] In addition, it is possible for the helicopter to fly at an airspeed where an excessive amount of the retreating blade stalls, which results in high vibration, pitch-up, and roll into the retreating blade.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p02] At the end of the 20th century, designers began working on helicopter noise reduction.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p02] Urban communities have often expressed great dislike of noisy aviation or noisy aircraft, and police and passenger helicopters can be unpopular because of the sound.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p02] The redesigns followed the closure of some city heliports and government action to constrain flight paths in national parks and other places of natural beauty.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p02] To reduce vibration, all helicopters have rotor adjustments for height and weight.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p02] A maladjusted helicopter can easily vibrate so much that it will shake itself apart.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p02] Blade height is adjusted by changing the pitch of the blade.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p02] Weight is adjusted by adding or removing weights on the rotor head and/or at the blade end caps.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p02] Most also have vibration dampers for height and pitch.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p02] Some also use mechanical feedback systems to sense and counter vibration.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p02] Usually the feedback system uses a mass as a "stable reference" and a linkage from the mass operates a flap to adjust the rotor's angle of attack to counter the vibration.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p02] Adjustment can be difficult in part because measurement of the vibration is hard, usually requiring sophisticated accelerometers mounted throughout the airframe and gearboxes.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p02] The most common blade vibration adjustment measurement system is to use a stroboscopic flash lamp, and observe painted markings or coloured reflectors on the underside of the rotor blades.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p02] The traditional low-tech system is to mount coloured chalk on the rotor tips, and see how they mark a linen sheet.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p02] Health and Usage Monitoring Systems (HUMS) provide vibration monitoring and rotor track and balance solutions to limit vibration.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p02] Gearbox vibration most often requires a gearbox overhaul or replacement.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p02] Gearbox or drive train vibrations can be extremely harmful to a pilot.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p02] The most severe effects are pain, numbness, and loss of tactile discrimination or dexterity.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p02] For a standard helicopter with a single main rotor, the tips of the main rotor blades produce a vortex ring in the air, which is a spiraling and circularly rotating airflow.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p02] As the craft moves forward, these vortices trail off behind the craft.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p02] When hovering with a forward diagonal crosswind, or moving in a forward diagonal direction, the spinning vortices trailing off the main rotor blades will align with the rotation of the tail rotor and cause an instability in flight control.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p02] When the trailing vortices colliding with the tail rotor are rotating in the same direction, this causes a loss of thrust from the tail rotor.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p02] When the trailing vortices rotate in the opposite direction of the tail rotor, thrust is increased.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p02] Use of the foot pedals is required to adjust the tail rotor's angle of attack, to compensate for these instabilities.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p02] These issues are due to the exposed tail rotor cutting through open air around the rear of the vehicle.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p02] This issue disappears when the tail is instead ducted, using an internal impeller enclosed in the tail and a jet of high pressure air sideways out of the tail, as the main rotor vortices can not impact the operation of an internal impeller.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p02] For a standard helicopter with a single main rotor, maintaining steady flight with a crosswind presents an additional flight control problem, where strong crosswinds from certain angles will increase or decrease lift from the main rotors.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p02] This effect is also triggered in a no-wind condition when moving the craft diagonally in various directions, depending on the direction of main rotor rotation.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p02] This can lead to a loss of control and a crash or hard landing when operating at low altitudes, due to the sudden unexpected loss of lift, and insufficient time and distance available to recover.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p02] Conventional rotary-wing aircraft use a set of complex mechanical gearboxes to convert the high rotation speed of gas turbines into the low speed required to drive main and tail rotors.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p02] Unlike powerplants, mechanical gearboxes cannot be duplicated (for redundancy) and have always been a major weak point in helicopter reliability.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p02] In-flight catastrophic gear failures often result in gearbox jamming and subsequent fatalities, whereas loss of lubrication can trigger onboard fire.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p02] Another weakness of mechanical gearboxes is their transient power limitation, due to structural fatigue limits.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p02] Recent EASA studies point to engines and transmissions as prime cause of crashes just after pilot errors.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p02] By contrast, electromagnetic transmissions do not use any parts in contact; hence lubrication can be drastically simplified, or eliminated.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p02] Their inherent redundancy offers good resilience to single point of failure.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p02] The absence of gears enables high power transient without impact on service life.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p02] The concept of electric propulsion applied to helicopter and electromagnetic drive was brought to reality by Pascal Chretien who designed, built and flew world's first man-carrying, free-flying electric helicopter.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p02] The concept was taken from the conceptual computer-aided design model on 10 September 2010 to the first testing at 30% power on 1 March 2011 – less than six months.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p02] The aircraft first flew on 12 August 2011.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p02] All development was conducted in Venelles, France.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p02] In addition to regulatory measures, helicopter operators are also supported by voluntary safety teams that analyze accident data and promote specific countermeasures.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p02] In the United States, for example, the U.S.
[src:helicopter/helicopter-p02] As with any moving vehicle, unsafe operation could result in loss of control, structural damage, or loss of life.
